<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5> take it out of someone • take it out on someone</xh5><p> <i>take it out of someone—</i>1. said of smth. that exhausts or weakens a person: He needs rest. The excitement of the past few days has <u>taken it out of</u> him. 2. exact satisfaction from a person (for an offence): Now, you need to find a way to get the money back or your boss will <u>take it out of</u> you.</p><p> <i>take it out on someone—</i>relieve one’s irritation, frustration, etc. by attacking smb. who is innocent: I know you’re upset at missing the train, but that’s no reason to <u>take it out on</u> the porter.</p> </entry>
